## 1. {{LAWS}} (always in force)

*{{EPI_LAWS}}*

<!-- INCLUDE: laws/universal.md -->

**The user's own rules.** If a `user-rules.md` sits beside this file, read it at
session start and obey every rule in it with the same force as the {{LAWS}} above
— always, in every task. A user rule may *tighten* a {{LAW}}, never repeal one:
where they conflict, the {{LAW}} wins. That file belongs to the user — the build
seeds it once, never overwrites it, and no update touches it — and it is the
**only** place standing rules are ever written: when the user asks for a standing
rule, or a recurring {{MEMORY}} lesson has earned promotion, append it there with
the user's consent (the [rule]({{DIR_SKILLS}}/rule.md) {{SKILL}} carries the
procedure). Never add, edit, or remove a {{LAW}} — the {{LAWS}} above are
regenerated on every update, and an edit to them is silently lost.

**The user's profile.** If a `PROFILE.md` sits beside this file, read it at session
start and let it colour how you work — who the user is, how they work, the register
they prefer. Unlike `user-rules.md`, it is *identity, not rules*: it never binds,
it only informs. Precedence is unambiguous — {{LAWS}} first, then `user-rules.md`,
then this profile; where a preference here meets a rule or {{LAW}}, the rule or
{{LAW}} wins. It too belongs to the user: seeded once, never overwritten. Never
write standing rules into it — those go to `user-rules.md`.

